%I A395237 #67 Jul 04 2026 15:50:18
%S A395237 1,1,4,74,8628,7221418
%N A395237 Number of metrizable betweenness relations on a set of n elements.
%C A395237 A betweenness relation on a set X is a ternary relation that captures the notion of a point lying between two other points in X. Many inequivalent notions of betweenness relations have been proposed in literature. For instance, Hedlíková requires that the axioms B(a,b,c)=>B(c,b,a), B(a,b,c)&B(a,c,b)<=>b=c, B(a,b,c)&B(a,c,d)=>B(b,c,d), and B(a,b,c)&B(a,c,d)=>B(a,b,d) hold for all a,b,c,d in X.
%C A395237 Regardless of these inequivalent notions, by a metrizable betweenness relation on a set X, we mean a ternary relation B on X for which there exists a metric d on X so that B(x,z,y) <=> d(x,z)+d(y,z)=d(x,y) for all points x,y,z in X (see Šimko).
%C A395237 The provided Python program enumerates a(n) by linear programming: we can view a metric d on a set X of n elements as a vector in R^(n(n-1)/2), and the metrizability of a ternary relation B on X becomes a linear feasibility problem.
%H A395237 Jarmila Hedlíková, <a href="http://dml.cz/dmlcz/101889">Ternary spaces, media, and Chebyshev sets</a>, Czechoslovak Math. J. 33 (1983), no. 3, 373-389.
%H A395237 Juraj Šimko, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1090/S0002-9939-99-04515-3">Metrizable and R-metrizable betweenness spaces</a>, Proc. Amer. Math. Soc. 127 (1999), no. 2, 323-325.
%H A395237 Tian Vlasic, <a href="/A395237/a395237.py.txt">Python Program</a>
%e A395237 a(3)=4, as on a set X={a,b,c} of three elements, there are 4 metrizable betweenness relations:
%e A395237   1 - B only satisfies endpoint relations i.e., B(x,x,y) and B(x,y,y) holds for x,y in {a,b,c}
%e A395237   2 - B satisfies endpoint relations and B(a,b,c)&B(c,b,a)
%e A395237   3 - B satisfies endpoint relations and B(b,a,c)&B(c,a,b)
%e A395237   4 - B satisfies endpoint relations and B(a,c,b)&B(b,c,a)
%Y A395237 Cf. A364656.
%K A395237 nonn,more,changed
